Data:

# Get the Data

# Read in the data manually

transitions <- readr::read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2023/2023-03-28/transitions.csv')
timezones <- readr::read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2023/2023-03-28/timezones.csv')
timezone_countries <- readr::read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2023/2023-03-28/timezone_countries.csv')
countries <- readr::read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2023/2023-03-28/countries.csv')
transitions2 <- transitions %>%
  left_join(timezones, by = c("zone" = "zone"))

transitions3 <- transitions2 %>%
  filter(latitude != 'NA')

Research Question:

How does the geographic location (longitude/latitude) of a time zones principal location affect how offset it is from the UTC in seconds?

Visualization:

world <- get_stamenmap(
  bbox = c(left = -180, bottom = -57, right = 179, top = 82.1),
  maptype = "terrain",
  zoom = 2
)

ggmap(world) + 
  geom_point(data = transitions3, aes(x = longitude, y = latitude, color = `offset`), alpha = 0.5, size = 2) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", color = "black", size = 1) +
  scale_color_gradient(low = "blue", high = "red") +
  annotate("text", x = 10, y = 80, label = "N", size = 5, fontface = "bold") +
  annotate("text", x = 5, y = -50, label = "S", size = 5, fontface = "bold") +
  annotate("text", x = -125, y = -5, label = "W", size = 5, fontface = "bold") +
  annotate("text", x = 150, y = 25, label = "E", size = 5, fontface = "bold") +
  theme_map()
